0:07:05.556,000 --> 0:07:07,000
humans that write like computers.

142
0:07:08.938,000 --> 0:07:09,000
So what do we take from all of this?

143
0:07:11.611,000 --> 0:07:14,000
Do we take that William Blake is somehow more of a human

144
0:07:14.792,000 --> 0:07:15,000
than Gertrude Stein?

145
0:07:16.065,000 --> 0:07:19,000
Or that Gertrude Stein is more of a computer than William Blake?

146
0:07:19.135,000 --> 0:07:2,000
(Laughter)

147
0:07:20.711,000 --> 0:07:22,000
These are questions I've been asking myself

148
0:07:23.058,000 --> 0:07:24,000
for around two years now,

149
0:07:24.547,000 --> 0:07:26,000
and I don't have any answers.

150
0:07:26.88,000 --> 0:07:28,000
But what I do have are a bunch of insights

151
0:07:29.234,000 --> 0:07:31,000
about our relationship with technology.

152
0:07:32.999,000 --> 0:07:35,000
So my first insight is that, for some reason,

153
0:07:36.632,000 --> 0:07:39,000
we associate poetry with being human.

154
0:07:40.197,000 --> 0:07:43,000
So that when we ask, "Can a computer write poetry?"

155
0:07:43.936,000 --> 0:07:44,000
we're also asking,

156
0:07:45.153,000 --> 0:07:46,000
"What does it mean to be human

157
0:07:46.975,000 --> 0:07:49,000
and how do we put boundaries around this category?

158
0:07:50.171,000 --> 0:07:53,000
How do we say who or what can be part of this category?"

159
0:07:54.376,000 --> 0:07:57,000
This is an essentially philosophical question, I believe,

160
0:07:57.751,000 --> 0:07:59,000
and it can't be answered with a yes or no test,

161
0:08:00.004,000 --> 0:08:01,000
like the Turing test.

162
0:08:01.805,000 --> 0:08:04,000
I also believe that Alan Turing understood this,

163
0:08:04.874,000 --> 0:08:07,000
and that when he devised his test back in 1950,

164
0:08:08.203,000 --> 0:08:1,000
he was doing it as a philosophical provocation.

165
0:08:13.124,000 --> 0:08:18,000
So my second insight is that, when we take the Turing test for poetry,

166
0:08:18.689,000 --> 0:08:21,000
we're not really testing the capacity of the computers

167
0:08:22.173,000 --> 0:08:24,000
because poetry-generating algorithms,

168
0:08:25.09,000 --> 0:08:29,000
they're pretty simple and have existed, more or less, since the 1950s.

169
0:08:31.055,000 --> 0:08:34,000
What we are doing with the Turing test for poetry, rather,

170
0:08:34.197,000 --> 0:08:38,000
is collecting opinions about what constitutes humanness.

171
0:08:40.313,000 --> 0:08:42,000
So, what I've figured out,

172
0:08:43.066,000 --> 0:08:45,000
we've seen this when earlier today,

173
0:08:46.062,000 --> 0:08:48,000
we say that William Blake is more of a human

174
0:08:48.564,000 --> 0:08:49,000
than Gertrude Stein.

175
0:08:50.153,000 --> 0:08:52,000
Of course, this doesn't mean that William Blake

176
0:08:52.639,000 --> 0:08:53,000
was actually more human

177
0:08:54.491,000 --> 0:08:56,000
or that Gertrude Stein was more of a computer.

178
0:08:57.533,000 --> 0:09:01,000
It simply means that the category of the human is unstable.

179
0:09:03.45,000 --> 0:09:05,000
This has led me to understand

180
0:09:05.548,000 --> 0:09:07,000
that the human is not a cold, hard fact.

181
0:09:08.832,000 --> 0:09:11,000
Rather, it is something that's constructed with our opinions

182
0:09:11.988,000 --> 0:09:13,000
and something that changes over time.

183
0:09:16.671,000 --> 0:09:2,000
So my final insight is that the computer, more or less,

184
0:09:21.174,000 --> 0:09:25,000
works like a mirror that reflects any idea of a human

185
0:09:25.204,000 --> 0:09:26,000
that we show it.

186
0:09:26.958,000 --> 0:09:27,000
We show it Emily Dickinson,

187
0:09:28.866,000 --> 0:09:3,000
it gives Emily Dickinson back to us.

188
0:09:31.768,000 --> 0:09:32,000
We show it William Blake,

189
0:09:33.626,000 --> 0:09:35,000
that's what it reflects back to us.

190
0:09:35.935,000 --> 0:09:36,000
We show it Gertrude Stein,

191
0:09:37.798,000 --> 0:09:39,000
what we get back is Gertrude Stein.

192
0:09:41.083,000 --> 0:09:43,000
More than any other bit of technology,

193
0:09:43.475,000 --> 0:09:48,000
the computer is a mirror that reflects any idea of the human we teach it.

194
0:09:50.061,000 --> 0:09:52,000
So I'm sure a lot of you have been hearing

195
0:09:52.372,000 --> 0:09:54,000
a lot about artificial intelligence recently.

196
0:09:56.694,000 --> 0:09:58,000
And much of the conversation is,

197
0:10:00.292,000 --> 0:10:01,000
can we build it?

198
0:10:02.383,000 --> 0:10:05,000
Can we build an intelligent computer?

199
0:10:05.542,000 --> 0:10:07,000
Can we build a creative computer?

200
0:10:08.329,000 --> 0:10:1,000
What we seem to be asking over and over

201
0:10:10.466,000 --> 0:10:12,000
is can we build a human-like computer?

202
0:10:13.961,000 --> 0:10:14,000
But what we've seen just now

203
0:10:15.541,000 --> 0:10:18,000
is that the human is not a scientific fact,

204
0:10:18.653,000 --> 0:10:21,000
that it's an ever-shifting, concatenating idea

205
0:10:22.207,000 --> 0:10:24,000
and one that changes over time.

206
0:10:24.762,000 --> 0:10:27,000
So that when we begin to grapple with the ideas

207
0:10:27.938,000 --> 0:10:29,000
of artificial intelligence in the future,

208
0:10:30.348,000 --> 0:10:31,000
we shouldn't only be asking ourselves,

209
0:10:32.277,000 --> 0:10:33,000
"Can we build it?"

210
0:10:33.669,000 --> 0:10:34,000
But we should also be asking ourselves,

211
0:10:35.587,000 --> 0:10:38,000
"What idea of the human do we want to have reflected back to us?"

212
0:10:39.82,000 --> 0:10:41,000
This is an essentially philosophical idea,

213
0:10:42.537,000 --> 0:10:44,000
and it's one that can't be answered with software alone,

214
0:10:45.558,000 --> 0:10:49,000
but I think requires a moment of species-wide, existential reflection.

215
0:10:51.04,000 --> 0:10:52,000
Thank you.

216
